</div>
<!-- TOPIC 8.1 -->
<h2>Topic 8.1 — Setting the Stage for the Cold War and Decolonization</h2>
<div class="region-card region-stage">
<h3>🌍 A New Postwar Order (1945)</h3>
<h4>Consequences of World War II</h4>
<ul>
<li>Europe devastated: 60–80 million dead worldwide; whole cities (Warsaw, Dresden, Stalingrad, Hiroshima) destroyed.</li>
<li>European powers <strong>economically exhausted</strong>; Britain and France dependent on U.S. aid.</li>
<li><strong>U.S. and USSR</strong> emerged as the only remaining great powers — with opposing systems (capitalist democracy vs. communist dictatorship).</li>
<li>Nuclear weapons created the possibility of civilization-ending war.</li>
</ul>
<h4>Wartime Conferences</h4>
<ul>
<li><strong>Yalta (February 1945):</strong> Stalin, Roosevelt, Churchill agree on occupation zones for Germany, Soviet entry into the Pacific war, and "free elections" in Eastern Europe — which Stalin violated.</li>
<li><strong>Potsdam (July–August 1945):</strong> Truman replaced the deceased Roosevelt; tensions over Poland and reparations increased.</li>
</ul>
<h4>New International Institutions</h4>
<ul>
<li><strong>United Nations</strong> (1945): Security Council with 5 permanent members (U.S., USSR, UK, France, China) each with veto.</li>
<li><strong>Bretton Woods</strong> (1944): <strong>IMF</strong> and <strong>World Bank</strong>; U.S. dollar pegged to gold and other currencies pegged to dollar — U.S. at the center of the postwar economy.</li>
<li><strong>GATT</strong> (1947) promoted freer trade.</li>
</ul>
<h4>Ideological Lines Drawn</h4>
<ul>
<li><strong>Churchill's "Iron Curtain"</strong> speech (Fulton, Missouri, 1946).</li>
<li><strong>Kennan's "long telegram"</strong> (1946) argued for <strong>containment</strong> of Soviet expansion.</li>
<li>Soviet forces remained in Eastern Europe; "people's democracies" installed as Soviet satellites by 1948.</li>
</ul>
<h4>The Stage for Decolonization</h4>
<ul>
<li>European empires weakened by war; many colonial soldiers returned demanding rights.</li>
<li><strong>Atlantic Charter</strong> (1941) invoked self-determination; colonized peoples cited it against their European rulers.</li>
<li>Both superpowers — for different reasons — opposed traditional European imperialism, creating political space for independence movements.</li>
</ul>
</div>
<!-- TOPIC 8.2 -->
<h2>Topic 8.2 — The Cold War</h2>
<div class="region-card region-coldwar">
<h3>❄️ Two Superpowers, One World</h3>
<figure class="photo">
<img src="https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/Special:FilePath/Berlin_Wall_1961-11-20.jpg?width=700" alt="Berlin Wall" />
<figcaption>The <strong>Berlin Wall</strong>, begun in August 1961, became the most visible symbol of Cold War division. It stood until its fall in November 1989.</figcaption>
</figure>
<h4>Containment and Early Crises (1945–1953)</h4>
<ul>
<li><strong>Truman Doctrine</strong> (1947): U.S. pledged to support "free peoples" resisting communism — aid to Greece and Turkey.</li>
<li><strong>Marshall Plan</strong> (1948): ~$13 billion to rebuild Western Europe and bind it to the U.S. economically.</li>
<li><strong>Berlin Blockade and Airlift</strong> (1948–49): Soviets cut off West Berlin; U.S. and UK airlifted supplies for nearly a year.</li>
<li><strong>NATO</strong> (1949): Western alliance guaranteeing collective defense. USSR responded with the <strong>Warsaw Pact</strong> (1955).</li>
<li><strong>Chinese Communist Revolution</strong> (1949): Mao Zedong's CCP won the civil war; China aligned with USSR (1950 treaty).</li>
<li><strong>Korean War</strong> (1950–1953): Communist North Korea invaded the South; U.S./UN forces intervened; ended in stalemate at the 38th parallel.</li>
</ul>
<h4>Superpower Competition in the Third World</h4>
<ul>
<li><strong>Proxy wars</strong> replaced direct confrontation: each superpower backed client regimes or insurgencies worldwide.</li>
<li>Major theaters: Vietnam, Afghanistan, Angola, Nicaragua, Ethiopia-Somalia.</li>
<li><strong>CIA and KGB</strong> covert operations, coups, and assassinations (e.g., U.S.-backed coups in Iran 1953, Guatemala 1954, Chile 1973).</li>
</ul>
<h4>Arms Race and Nuclear Brinkmanship</h4>
<ul>
<li><strong>USSR detonated an atomic bomb</strong> (1949) and hydrogen bomb (1953); U.S. responded with H-bomb (1952).</li>
<li>Doctrine of <strong>mutually assured destruction (MAD)</strong>: overwhelming retaliation deterred first use.</li>
<li><strong>Space race</strong>: Sputnik (1957), Gagarin (1961), Apollo moon landing (1969).</li>
<li><strong>Cuban Missile Crisis</strong> (October 1962): USSR deployed missiles in Cuba; Kennedy blockade; resolved by Soviet withdrawal in exchange for U.S. missiles removed from Turkey.</li>
</ul>
<h4>Détente and Renewed Tensions (1960s–80s)</h4>
<ul>
<li><strong>Détente</strong> (1960s–70s): Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty (1968), SALT I (1972), Helsinki Accords (1975).</li>
<li><strong>Nixon to China</strong> (1972) split the communist bloc further (Sino-Soviet split had deepened since 1960).</li>
<li><strong>Second Cold War</strong> (late 1970s–early 80s): Soviet invasion of Afghanistan (1979), Reagan's SDI/"Star Wars" and military buildup.</li>
</ul>
</div>
<!-- TOPIC 8.3 -->
<h2>Topic 8.3 — Effects of the Cold War</h2>
<div class="region-card region-effects">
<h3>🌐 How the Superpower Rivalry Shaped the World</h3>
<h4>Military Alliances and Divided States</h4>
<ul>
<li><strong>NATO vs. Warsaw Pact</strong> in Europe.</li>
<li><strong>Divided nations</strong>: Germany (1949–1990), Korea (1945–present), Vietnam (1954–1975), China/Taiwan (1949–present).</li>
<li><strong>Berlin Wall</strong> (1961–1989) symbolized the split within Germany and Europe.</li>
</ul>
<h4>Proxy Wars and Interventions</h4>
<ul>
<li><strong>Vietnam War</strong> (1955–1975): U.S. poured in over 500,000 troops; ended with communist victory and U.S. withdrawal.</li>
<li><strong>Afghan War</strong> (1979–1989): Soviet invasion, U.S. arming of mujahideen — a contributing factor to Soviet collapse.</li>
<li><strong>Angola and Mozambique</strong>: Cold War-aligned civil wars after Portuguese decolonization.</li>
<li><strong>Latin America</strong>: U.S. backed right-wing regimes (Chile 1973 Pinochet coup, Argentina, Nicaragua's Contras); Cubans supported left-wing guerrillas.</li>
</ul>
<h4>Nuclear Arms and Fear</h4>
<ul>
<li>By the 1980s, U.S. and USSR each possessed tens of thousands of nuclear warheads.</li>
<li>Culture of Cold War fear: civil defense drills, fallout shelters, nuclear-themed films and literature.</li>
</ul>
<h4>Cultural and Economic Effects</h4>
<ul>
<li><strong>Peace movements</strong>: anti-nuclear ("Ban the Bomb," CND in Britain; Europe's nuclear freeze).</li>
<li>Global spread of U.S. <strong>consumer culture</strong> (Coca-Cola, Hollywood, rock 'n' roll) and Soviet-bloc cultural exchanges (ballet, cinema).</li>
<li>Massive military spending shaped both economies; "<strong>military-industrial complex</strong>" (Eisenhower's warning, 1961).</li>
</ul>
<h4>Non-Aligned Movement</h4>
<ul>
<li><strong>Bandung Conference</strong> (1955, Indonesia): 29 African and Asian states affirmed solidarity against colonialism and Cold War blocs.</li>
<li><strong>Non-Aligned Movement</strong> (formalized 1961, Belgrade): led by Nehru (India), Tito (Yugoslavia), Nasser (Egypt), Sukarno (Indonesia), Nkrumah (Ghana).</li>
<li>Attempted a "Third Way" — economic development without committing to either superpower.</li>
</ul>
</div>
<!-- TOPIC 8.4 -->
<h2>Topic 8.4 — Spread of Communism after 1900</h2>
<div class="region-card region-comm">
<h3>🚩 Revolutions and Regimes</h3>
<figure class="photo">
<img src="https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/Special:FilePath/Mao_Zedong_portrait.jpg?width=500" alt="Mao Zedong portrait" />
<figcaption><strong>Mao Zedong</strong> (1893–1976), founder of the People's Republic of China (1949) and leader of the Cultural Revolution (1966–76).</figcaption>
</figure>
<h4>Russia/USSR (1917–1991)</h4>
<ul>
<li><strong>Bolshevik Revolution</strong> (1917) — first communist state.</li>
<li><strong>Stalin's USSR</strong>: Five-Year Plans, forced collectivization, Great Purges (1936–38), Gulag.</li>
<li>After WWII, the USSR created a ring of <strong>satellite states</strong> in Eastern Europe (Poland, Hungary, Czechoslovakia, East Germany, Bulgaria, Romania).</li>
</ul>
<h4>China (1949– )</h4>
<ul>
<li>Mao's <strong>CCP</strong> defeated the Guomindang in the civil war; founded the <strong>People's Republic of China</strong> (1949).</li>
<li><strong>Great Leap Forward</strong> (1958–62): attempted rapid industrialization through communes; caused the deadliest famine in history (tens of millions dead).</li>
<li><strong>Cultural Revolution</strong> (1966–76): Mao mobilized Red Guards against "bourgeois" elements; destroyed much of traditional culture, persecuted intellectuals.</li>
<li>After Mao's death (1976), <strong>Deng Xiaoping</strong> introduced market reforms while keeping one-party rule.</li>
</ul>
<h4>Latin America — Cuba and Beyond</h4>
<ul>
<li><strong>Cuban Revolution</strong> (1959): <strong>Fidel Castro</strong> and Che Guevara overthrew Batista; Cuba became a Soviet-aligned communist state.</li>
<li><strong>Nicaragua</strong>: Sandinistas took power (1979); U.S. backed Contras in the 1980s.</li>
<li><strong>Chile</strong>: socialist Salvador Allende elected (1970); overthrown in a U.S.-backed coup (1973) by Pinochet.</li>
</ul>
<h4>Asia</h4>
<ul>
<li><strong>North Korea</strong> (1948): Kim Il-sung's dynastic communist state.</li>
<li><strong>Vietnam</strong>: Ho Chi Minh led nationalist communist movement from 1941; after defeating the French (1954) and the U.S. (1975), reunified Vietnam as communist (1976).</li>
<li><strong>Cambodia</strong>: Khmer Rouge under <strong>Pol Pot</strong> seized power (1975–79); roughly 1.7–2 million people killed in the Cambodian genocide.</li>
</ul>
<h4>Africa</h4>
<ul>
<li><strong>Angola</strong>: MPLA (backed by USSR/Cuba) vs. UNITA (backed by U.S./South Africa).</li>
<li><strong>Mozambique</strong>: FRELIMO government aligned with socialist states.</li>
<li><strong>Ethiopia</strong>: Mengistu's Derg regime (1974–91) aligned with the USSR.</li>
</ul>
</div>
<!-- TOPIC 8.5 -->
<h2>Topic 8.5 — Decolonization after 1900</h2>
<div class="region-card region-decol">
<h3>🕊️ Independence Movements in Africa, Asia, and the Caribbean</h3>
<figure class="photo">
<img src="https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/Special:FilePath/Mahatma-Gandhi%2C_studio%2C_1931.jpg?width=500" alt="Mahatma Gandhi" />
<figcaption><strong>Mohandas K. "Mahatma" Gandhi</strong> (1869–1948). Using <em>satyagraha</em> (nonviolent resistance), he led India's independence movement through campaigns such as the 1930 Salt March.</figcaption>
</figure>
<h4>India</h4>
<ul>
<li><strong>Indian National Congress</strong> (founded 1885) grew into a mass movement after WWI.</li>
<li><strong>Gandhi</strong>'s <em>satyagraha</em>: nonviolent civil disobedience, symbolized by the <strong>Salt March</strong> (1930).</li>
<li><strong>Jawaharlal Nehru</strong> led political strategy; <strong>Muhammad Ali Jinnah</strong> and the Muslim League demanded a separate Muslim state.</li>
<li><strong>1947 independence and partition</strong>: British India split into India and Pakistan; ~14 million displaced and ~1 million killed in the violence that followed.</li>
</ul>
<h4>Middle East and North Africa</h4>
<ul>
<li><strong>Egypt</strong>: <strong>Gamal Abdel Nasser</strong> seized power (1952); nationalized the Suez Canal (1956). The <strong>Suez Crisis</strong> embarrassed Britain and France and signaled the end of old-style European imperialism.</li>
<li><strong>Israel</strong> declared independence (1948) amid conflict with neighboring Arab states; produced the Palestinian <em>nakba</em> ("catastrophe") displacing ~700,000 Palestinians.</li>
<li><strong>Algeria</strong>: eight-year war of independence against France (1954–62); extraordinarily violent; led by the FLN.</li>
</ul>
<h4>Sub-Saharan Africa</h4>
<ul>
<li><strong>Ghana</strong>: <strong>Kwame Nkrumah</strong> led the first sub-Saharan African colony to independence (1957).</li>
<li><strong>"Year of Africa"</strong> (1960): 17 countries gained independence.</li>
<li><strong>Kenya</strong>: <strong>Mau Mau Uprising</strong> (1952–60) preceded independence (1963) under Jomo Kenyatta.</li>
<li><strong>Congo</strong>: chaotic decolonization from Belgium (1960); Patrice Lumumba assassinated (1961).</li>
<li>Portuguese Africa (<strong>Angola, Mozambique, Guinea-Bissau</strong>): prolonged wars of liberation; independent 1975.</li>
<li><strong>Zimbabwe</strong>: independence from white-minority Rhodesia (1980).</li>
<li><strong>South Africa</strong>: apartheid (1948–94) maintained white minority rule despite global sanctions; Nelson Mandela imprisoned 1962–1990.</li>
</ul>
<h4>Southeast Asia</h4>
<ul>
<li><strong>Indonesia</strong>: Sukarno declared independence from the Netherlands (1945); formally recognized 1949.</li>
<li><strong>Vietnam</strong>: Ho Chi Minh declared independence (1945); defeated France at <strong>Dien Bien Phu</strong> (1954), then the U.S. in 1975.</li>
<li><strong>Philippines</strong>: independence from the U.S. (1946).</li>
</ul>
<h4>Caribbean</h4>
<ul>
<li><strong>Jamaica and Trinidad &amp; Tobago</strong> gained independence from Britain (1962).</li>
<li><strong>Barbados</strong> (1966), Bahamas (1973).</li>
<li><strong>Cuba</strong>: independence long since achieved (1902); 1959 revolution transformed it into a communist state.</li>
</ul>
<h4>Methods of Decolonization</h4>
<ul>
<li><strong>Nonviolence</strong>: India, Ghana, much of sub-Saharan Africa.</li>
<li><strong>Armed struggle</strong>: Algeria, Vietnam, Angola, Mozambique, Kenya.</li>
<li><strong>Negotiated transitions</strong>: Most British and French possessions eventually negotiated terms.</li>
<li><strong>Cold War alignment</strong> often shaped which superpower backed which movement.</li>
</ul>
</div>
<!-- TOPIC 8.6 -->
<h2>Topic 8.6 — Newly Independent States</h2>
<div class="region-card region-newstate">
<h3>🏛️ Building Nations in a Cold War World</h3>
<h4>Political Challenges</h4>
<ul>
<li><strong>Colonial borders</strong> often cut across ethnic and linguistic groups — a recipe for future conflict (e.g., Nigeria, Sudan, Rwanda).</li>
<li><strong>Civil wars</strong>: Biafra (Nigeria, 1967–70), Congo, Sudan, Ethiopia-Eritrea.</li>
<li><strong>Coups and authoritarian rule</strong> became common as young militaries seized power (e.g., Idi Amin, Uganda, 1971).</li>
<li><strong>One-party states</strong> and <strong>presidents-for-life</strong> emerged even in places that had begun as democracies.</li>
</ul>
<h4>Economic Strategies</h4>
<ul>
<li><strong>Import substitution industrialization (ISI)</strong>: state-led industry behind tariff walls (widespread in Latin America, India).</li>
<li><strong>Export-led growth</strong>: the "<strong>Asian Tigers</strong>" (South Korea, Taiwan, Hong Kong, Singapore) industrialized rapidly through export-oriented policies.</li>
<li><strong>Resource-based economies</strong>: oil wealth made states like Saudi Arabia, Iran, Venezuela, and Nigeria geopolitically important.</li>
<li><strong>Dependency and debt</strong>: many countries borrowed heavily in the 1970s; 1980s debt crises led to IMF structural adjustment programs with painful effects.</li>
</ul>
<h4>Important Examples</h4>
<ul>
<li><strong>India</strong>: Largest democracy; Nehru's mixed economy; 1971 war created Bangladesh; Indira Gandhi's emergency rule (1975–77).</li>
<li><strong>Egypt</strong>: Nasser's pan-Arabism, Aswan High Dam (1970), 1967 Six-Day War defeat, 1979 peace with Israel under Sadat.</li>
<li><strong>Ghana</strong>: Nkrumah's dream of African socialism faltered; overthrown 1966.</li>
<li><strong>South Korea</strong>: dictatorship under Park Chung-hee built a modern industrial economy; democratized in the late 1980s.</li>
<li><strong>Iran</strong>: U.S.-backed Shah modernized rapidly; overthrown in the <strong>1979 Islamic Revolution</strong> — Ayatollah Khomeini established the Islamic Republic.</li>
</ul>
<h4>Migration</h4>
<ul>
<li><strong>Postcolonial migration</strong>: South Asians to Britain, North Africans to France, Caribbean migrants to the U.S. and UK.</li>
<li>Formation of <strong>multicultural societies</strong> in former imperial centers.</li>
<li><strong>Refugee flows</strong> tied to war and partition (Palestinian, Bangladeshi, Vietnamese "boat people").</li>
</ul>
</div>
<!-- TOPIC 8.7 -->
<h2>Topic 8.7 — Global Resistance to Established Power Structures</h2>
<div class="region-card region-resist">
<h3>🪧 Movements from Below</h3>
<h4>Civil Rights and Racial Equality</h4>
<ul>
<li><strong>U.S. Civil Rights Movement</strong>: Brown v. Board (1954), Montgomery Bus Boycott (1955–56), March on Washington (1963), Civil Rights Act (1964), Voting Rights Act (1965). Leaders: Martin Luther King Jr., Rosa Parks, Malcolm X.</li>
<li><strong>South African Anti-Apartheid</strong>: Sharpeville Massacre (1960); African National Congress (<strong>Nelson Mandela</strong>); global boycotts and sanctions. Apartheid dismantled 1990–94; Mandela elected president 1994.</li>
<li><strong>Indigenous rights</strong>: American Indian Movement (AIM, founded 1968); global push for indigenous recognition.</li>
</ul>
<figure class="photo">
<img src="https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/Special:FilePath/Nelson_Mandela_1994_%28cropped%29.jpg?width=500" alt="Nelson Mandela in 1994" />
<figcaption><strong>Nelson Mandela</strong> in 1994, the year he was inaugurated as the first president of a fully democratic South Africa, ending the apartheid system.</figcaption>
</figure>
<h4>Women's Rights</h4>
<ul>
<li><strong>Second-wave feminism</strong> (1960s–70s): Betty Friedan (<em>The Feminine Mystique</em>, 1963), Simone de Beauvoir, NOW, Gloria Steinem.</li>
<li><strong>UN Decade for Women</strong> (1975–85); Mexico City (1975) and Beijing (1995) conferences.</li>
<li>Growing legal reforms: contraception access, anti-discrimination laws, property rights, women's suffrage spreading to remaining holdouts (e.g., Swiss women gained federal vote 1971; Saudi women in municipal elections 2015).</li>
</ul>
<h4>Student and Youth Movements</h4>
<ul>
<li><strong>1968 global wave</strong>: Paris (May 1968), Prague Spring (crushed by Soviet tanks), Mexico City (Tlatelolco massacre), U.S. anti-Vietnam protests.</li>
<li>Cultural transformation: rock music, counterculture, sexual revolution, critique of bureaucratic society.</li>
</ul>
<h4>Environmental Movement</h4>
<ul>
<li>Rachel Carson's <em>Silent Spring</em> (1962).</li>
<li>First Earth Day (1970); Greenpeace (1971).</li>
<li>Stockholm (1972), Rio (1992) UN environmental conferences.</li>
</ul>
<h4>LGBTQ+ Rights</h4>
<ul>
<li><strong>Stonewall riots</strong> (New York, 1969) helped launch the modern gay-rights movement; decades of activism followed.</li>
</ul>
<h4>Religious Resurgence</h4>
<ul>
<li><strong>Islamic revivalism</strong>: Muslim Brotherhood (Egypt), Iranian Revolution (1979), Afghan mujahideen.</li>
<li><strong>Christian evangelical movements</strong> in the Americas and Africa.</li>
<li><strong>Hindu nationalism</strong> in India (rise of the BJP from the 1980s).</li>
</ul>
<h4>Terrorism</h4>
<ul>
<li>Nationalist (IRA, ETA, PLO), ideological (Red Brigades, Baader-Meinhof), and religious extremist (al-Qaeda after 1988) terrorism rose in this period.</li>
