<!-- TOPIC 8.8 -->
<h2>Topic 8.8 — End of the Cold War</h2>
<div class="region-card region-endcold">
<h3>🕊️ 1985–1991</h3>
<figure class="photo">
<img src="https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/Special:FilePath/West_and_East_Germans_at_the_Brandenburg_Gate_in_1989.jpg?width=700" alt="East and West Germans at Brandenburg Gate, 1989" />
<figcaption>East and West Germans together atop the Berlin Wall at the Brandenburg Gate, November 1989 — an iconic image of the Cold War's end.</figcaption>
</figure>
<h4>Causes of Soviet Decline</h4>
<ul>
<li><strong>Economic stagnation</strong>: planned economy unable to match Western innovation or consumer goods.</li>
<li><strong>Arms race</strong>: Reagan-era U.S. military buildup strained Soviet budgets.</li>
<li><strong>Afghanistan quagmire</strong> (1979–89): the USSR's "Vietnam."</li>
<li><strong>Nationalist unrest</strong> in the Baltic republics, Ukraine, and the Caucasus.</li>
<li><strong>Dissidents</strong> (Solzhenitsyn, Sakharov) and Eastern European opposition (Poland's <strong>Solidarity</strong>, 1980).</li>
</ul>
<h4>Gorbachev's Reforms</h4>
<ul>
<li><strong>Mikhail Gorbachev</strong> became General Secretary in 1985.</li>
<li><strong>Glasnost</strong> ("openness"): loosened censorship, encouraged public debate.</li>
<li><strong>Perestroika</strong> ("restructuring"): limited market reforms to the Soviet economy.</li>
<li>Renounced the <strong>Brezhnev Doctrine</strong> — signaling that the USSR would not intervene militarily to save communist regimes in Eastern Europe.</li>
</ul>
<h4>Revolutions of 1989</h4>
<ul>
<li><strong>Poland</strong>: Solidarity won semi-free elections.</li>
<li><strong>Hungary</strong> opened its border with Austria.</li>
<li><strong>East Germany</strong>: mass protests; the <strong>Berlin Wall fell</strong> on 9 November 1989.</li>
<li><strong>Czechoslovakia</strong>: Velvet Revolution (Václav Havel).</li>
<li><strong>Romania</strong>: violent overthrow of Ceaușescu.</li>
</ul>
<h4>China's Divergent Path — Tiananmen Square</h4>
<ul>
<li>In 1989, Chinese students occupied Tiananmen Square demanding political reform.</li>
<li>On 4 June 1989, the Chinese Communist Party crushed the protests — preserving one-party rule even as Deng continued market reforms.</li>
</ul>
<h4>Collapse of the Soviet Union</h4>
<ul>
<li>Baltic states declared independence (1990); Ukraine, Belarus, Russia, and other republics followed.</li>
<li>Failed August 1991 coup against Gorbachev by hardliners accelerated the end.</li>
<li>On <strong>25 December 1991</strong>, Gorbachev resigned; the USSR formally dissolved into 15 independent states.</li>
</ul>
<h4>Immediate Consequences</h4>
<ul>
<li><strong>Unipolar moment</strong>: U.S. as sole superpower.</li>
<li>Former Warsaw Pact members joined NATO and the EU in the 1990s-2000s.</li>
<li><strong>Yugoslavia</strong> disintegrated into bloody wars (1991–99) — including the Bosnian War and Kosovo.</li>
<li>Post-Soviet economic turmoil in Russia; rise of oligarchs; later Putin's authoritarianism (from 2000).</li>
</ul>
</div>
