<h4>Continuities</h4>
<ul>
<li>Industrial, globally connected economies continued to integrate through the Cold War era.</li>
<li>Nationalism remained a dominant political force.</li>
<li>Inequalities between global "North" and "South" persisted and in some ways deepened.</li>
<li>Violent conflict continued worldwide, often fueled by superpower competition.</li>
</ul>
<h4>Changes</h4>
<ul>
<li><strong>End of formal European empires</strong>: new sovereign states in Africa, Asia, and the Caribbean.</li>
<li><strong>Rise and fall of Soviet communism</strong>; Chinese communism reshaped into a market-Leninist system.</li>
<li><strong>Superpower rivalry replaced multipolar great-power politics</strong>, then gave way in 1991 to a U.S.-led "unipolar moment."</li>
<li><strong>Global human rights regime</strong> (UN, civil rights, women's rights) shaped political vocabulary worldwide.</li>
</ul>
<h4>Looking Forward to Unit 9</h4>
<ul>
<li>Post-1991 <strong>globalization</strong> accelerated with the end of the Cold War.</li>
<li>Ethnic and religious conflicts reemerged (Yugoslavia, Rwanda, Chechnya).</li>
<li>Technology (internet, mobile phones) revolutionized communication.</li>
<li>New challenges emerged: climate change, terrorism, pandemics, rising inequality.</li>
</ul>
